Create a Selfexpanding Textarea using Javascript', 'http://www.alexpeta.ro/article/create-a-selfexpanding-textarea-using-javascript/', '<p>   This post today is about how to create a Facebook-like auto expanding textarea.</p>
<p>   In order to solve this problem I looked to Facebook in order to somehow reversengineer it and failed gracefully, the javascript code there is pretty complex and out of my understanding and decided to start from scratch.</p>
<p>   After creating a html textarea element and trying to make some simple calculus with character counting, i had noticed that fonts /characters differ from browser to browser. i.e. Lets say i have &nbsp;a &lt;span&gt; element , font family Arial, 12px size, they are 2 diffrent actual pixel sizes in Firefox vs IE.</p>
<p>   As the &lt;textarea&gt; element doesnt self-expand, the question I&#39;ve asked myself was : what html tag element is self exapading vertically when filled with text ? Why not have the text fill a &lt;div&gt; element and transfer its size to the &lt;textarea&gt; ?&nbsp;</p>
<p>   So lets get started with the code, first we have the some CSS :</p>
<pre class="prettyprint">
.big_wrap{
  background-color: #EDEFF4;
  border-bottom: 1px solid #E5EAF1;
  margin-top: 2px;
  padding: 5px 5px 4px;
}
.fontStyle{
  direction: ltr;
  font-family: &quot;lucida grande&quot;,tahoma,verdana,arial,sans-serif;
  font-size: 11px;
  text-align: left;
}
#Test{
  left:-9999px;
  position: absolute;
  height: auto;
  width: auto;
  font-family: &quot;lucida grande&quot;,tahoma,verdana,arial,sans-serif;
  font-size: 11px;
}
#comm{
  width:340px;
  border:1px solid #BDC7D8;
  height:13px;
  padding:3px;
  overflow:hidden;
  resize: none;
  word-wrap: break-word;
  white-space: pre-wrap;
  z-index:2;
}
.btn {
  background-color: #5B74A8;
  border: 0 none;
  color: White;
  cursor: pointer;
  display: block;
  font-weight: bold;
  padding: 3px 8px;
}
#highlighter{
  width:340px;
  white-space: pre-wrap;
  word-wrap: break-word;
  position:absolute;
  color:trasparent;
  z-index:1;
  border:1px solid #003;
  visibility:hidden;
  padding:3px;
  margin:1px;
}
</pre>
<p>   Here we have defied some styles to resemble the facebook interface.</p>
<p>   Next is the HTML :</p>
<pre class="prettyprint">
&lt;table cellpadding=&quot;0&quot; cellspacing=&quot;0&quot; align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;
  &lt;tbody&gt;
    &lt;tr&gt;
	  &lt;td&gt;
	    &lt;div style=&quot;&quot; class=&quot;fontStyle&quot; id=&quot;highlighter&quot; name=&quot;highlighter&quot;&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
		&lt;div class=&quot;big_wrap&quot;&gt;
		  &lt;div class=&quot;wrap&quot;&gt;
		    &lt;textarea id=&quot;comm&quot; class=&quot;fontStyle&quot;  onkeypress=&quot;enlarge(this,event)&quot; onkeyup=&quot;enlarge(this,event)&quot; onkeydown=&quot;enlarge(this,event)&quot; onblur=&quot;enlarge(this,event)&quot; onfocus=&quot;enlarge(this,event)&quot;&gt;&lt;/textarea&gt;
			&lt;input class=&quot;mentionsHidden&quot; type=&quot;hidden&quot; autocomplete=&quot;off&quot; name=&quot;add_comment_text&quot; value=&quot;&quot;&gt; 
		 &lt;/div&gt;
		&lt;/div&gt;
	&lt;/td&gt;
	&lt;/tr&gt;
	&lt;tr&gt;
	   &lt;td style=&quot;height:20px;padding-top:2px;&quot; align=&quot;right&quot;&gt;
		 &lt;input type=&quot;submit&quot; class=&quot;btn&quot; id=&quot;btnAddComm&quot; value=&quot;Add Comment&quot; name=&quot;btnAddComm&quot;&gt;
	   &lt;/td&gt;
	&lt;/tr&gt; 
	&lt;tr&gt;
	  &lt;td style=&quot;height:20px;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/td&gt;
	&lt;/tr&gt;
  &lt;/tbody&gt;
&lt;/table&gt;  
</pre>     <p>   And finally the Javascript code :</p>
<p>   &nbsp;</p>
<pre class="prettyprint">
function enlarge(c,e){
  if(c.value.length == 0){
    document.getElementById(&#39;highlighter&#39;).innerHTML = &#39;&#39;;
	c.style.height == &#39;13px&#39;;
  }
  else
  {
    document.getElementsByName(&#39;add_comment_text&#39;).item(0).value = c.value;
	document.getElementById(&#39;highlighter&#39;).innerHTML = c.value;
	var h = document.getElementById(&#39;highlighter&#39;).clientHeight-6;
	c.style.height = h+&#39;px&#39;;
  }
}
</pre>  <p>   So what i have created here is my &lt;textarea&gt; element with the id comm, which i have binded with keypress/keydown/keyup/onblur/onfocus events to call the enlarge function.</p>  <p>   The function will put the textarea content in our &quot;highlighter&quot; div, which as you noticed must have the same width /style definition as the textarea, and the get the height of the highlighter and send it to the textarea.</p>

http://www.alexpeta.ro/article/secret-santa-random-list-generator-using-csharp-.net/', '<p>   As Christmas is just around the courner, the corporate life is organizing, as we do every year, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Secret_Santa">Secret Santa</a>. We are beeing each others Santa&#39;s by write names of a piece of paper, put them in a bowl, and take turns in picking one ticket, and then buying the selected persons a present withing a given budget or course (this operation is repeaded if you pick your name up).</p>  <p>   Now today, because our team is spread across 2 diffrent buildings, us techies from the bunch decided to skip the trip over and build a web app to do the lottery for us.</p>  <p>   The app has an interface for WishLists with an underlying table that contains&nbsp;contact info, pic url, and present details&nbsp;and on the day we decide to run the lottery app, it will generate pairs of 2 people and send them to each &quot;Santa&quot; with the designated person&#39;s pic and wishlist. Of course a lot of ideas flowed and it prooved out to be a lot of fun.</p>  <p>   This was build using <a href="http://apex.oracle.com/i/index.html">Oracle Application Express 4.1</a>, but hey, i just wanted to do the same logic in C#.NET 3.5</p>  <p>   For this exercise i&#39;ll be using a Console Application , and List&lt;String&gt; with the emails as my data source.</p>
<pre class="prettyprint">
class Program      
{            

   static bool TestMatch(List<string> toTest)
   {
     foreach (string p in toTest)
     {
        if (p0 == p1)  
        return false; 
     }

     return true;    
   }

   static void Main(string args) 
   {
     Stopwatch w = new Stopwatch(); 
     List<string> all =  new List<string> { "claudiu@email.com","raluca@email.com",
                                            "alex@email.com","madalina@email.com",
                                            "diana@email.com","mihaela@email.com",
                                            "georgeta@email.com" ,"maria@email.com" ,
                                            "adriana@email.com","valentina@email.com" ,
                                            "iulia@email.com","luciana@email.com" ,
                                            "elena@email.com","amalia@email.com" ,"vava@email.com" };
     List<string> theMatchup = new List<string>();           
     do{
           List<string> posibilities = all.ToList();
         theMatchup.Clear();
         Random r = new Random();
         foreach (string person in all)
         {
           if (posibilities.Count > 0)
           { 
              int generated = 0;
              do{
                  generated = r.Next(0, posibilities.Count); 
                } while (person == posibilitiesgenerated);

            theMatchup.Add(new string { person, posibilitiesgenerated });
            posibilities.Remove(posibilitiesgenerated);
           } 
          } 
        }while (!TestMatch(theMatchup));

        foreach (string p in theMatchup)
        { 
          Console.WriteLine("{0} ---------------> {1}",p0,p1); 
        }

        Console.WriteLine(TestMatch(theMatchup));

        w.Stop();
        Console.WriteLine("Elapsed : {0}",w.Elapsed);
     }      
}  
 </pre>
 <p>   So first of all we will need something to store our results :List of string that will act as our pair holder:</p>
 <pre class="prettyprint">
 List<string> theMatchup = new List<string>(); </pre>
 <p>   After creating a duplicate list, we&#39;ll use Random r to generate a number for us to &quot;pop&quot; from the auxiliary list,but beeing aware that the values musn&#39;t match :</p>
 <pre class="prettyprint">
   List<string> posibilities = all.ToList();

   theMatchup.Clear();

   Random r = new Random();
   foreach (string person in all)
   {
     if (posibilities.Count > 0)
    {
       int generated = 0;

       do{
           generated = r.Next(0, posibilities.Count);
         } while (person == posibilitiesgenerated);

      theMatchup.Add(new string { person, posibilitiesgenerated });
      posibilities.Remove(posibilitiesgenerated);

    }
   }</pre>
  <p>   Finally we check the results, and repeat the whole process if necessary</p> 
<pre class="prettyprint">
  static bool TestMatch(List<string> toTest)
  {
    foreach (string p in toTest)
    {
      if (p0 == p1)
      return false;
    }
    return true;
  }
 </pre>
 <p>   Not sure how this scales up, when you are a large department but on this example here : Elapsed : 00:00:00.0017831</p>
